🔑 Simple Explanation:
The client secret is ONLY used to GET the token, but the token itself is tied to the USER, not the client.

📋 What Happens:
API Gateway uses its client secret to get a token for itself (if needed for service-to-service calls)

Frontend gets a user token using a public client (no secret)

That user token works for ALL microservices because:

Keycloak signed it

Every microservice can verify the signature

The token contains the user's identity and roles

No client secret needed for validation

Step 1: Frontend → Spring Cloud Gateway
        Request: GET /api/products
        Header: Authorization: Bearer eyJ...

Step 2: Spring Cloud Gateway validates token
        Calls Keycloak: "Is this token valid?"
        Keycloak: "YES"

Step 3: Spring Cloud Gateway forwards to Product Service
        Request: GET /api/products
        Header: Authorization: Bearer eyJ...  (SAME token)

Step 4: Product Service receives request with token
        Product Service can also validate (if configured)

Step 5: Product Service returns products

Step 6: Spring Cloud Gateway returns products to Frontend


